		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>&#44; <date>1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> Jan. 1863</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I wrote you on <date>23rd</date><lb/> ult. since when I have been placed in posses<lb/>sion of yours of <date>8<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> ult.  The subject being<lb/> an unpleasant one&#44; I reply thereto only to cor<lb/>rect any erroneous impressions which may<lb/> have been formed on your mind.  If my fa<lb/>ther has mentioned any names I would assure<lb/> you that the small balance which was due<lb/> me has been repaid&#44; the delay being but a<lb/> temporary indulgence which on my part&#44; I<lb/> was desirous of shewing&#44; therefore quite a pri<lb/>vate affair.  Then Sterling being the only<lb/> remittance none made to the <placeName>States</placeName>&#44; I had<lb/> to include your dues in a Bill I sent to <placeName>Bos<lb/>ton</placeName>&#44; sending you another for the amt. With<lb/> 10&#37; dis. while if the first realize the rate</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>non quoted&#44; I shall make sufficiently on the lat<lb/>ter to repay myself for any trifle I may have open.<lb/>  I trust that this explanation will satisfy you&#44;<lb/> as it should&#59; and that you will excuse any<lb/>thing unpleasant in my Father&#39;s letter for you<lb/> must know that but for his unfortunate mal<lb/>ady which you have noticed&#44; he could not have<lb/> mentioned anything of the kind.  We have already<lb/> had reason to complain that more care should<lb/> not have been taken to prevent his communica<lb/>ting with persons abroad without his letters pas<lb/>sing thro&#39; the Dr&#39;s hands.  But I am sorry that<lb/> you should call the distribution of a few copies<lb/> of a religious work&#44; a kindness&#44; or that you shld.<lb/> find therein any reason to regret my being person<lb/>ally unknown to you.  You remind me that<lb/> I was the one who took the liberty of commencing<lb/> the correspondence.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I would thank you for your kind sympathy<lb/> and good wishes&#44; remaining&#44; Rev. Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)">Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><persName role="author">D. M. Pizal</persName></p>
		</body>
